Once Payle had left the room, he turned to the far corner, where a small boy hid from view behind piles of papers, and old armors,&quot; Disciple, did you hear all of that?&quot;<br>
&quot; Aye, my Thresher, I heard it all,&quot; said one of Daiunus's chosen.<br>
&quot; Good.. follow her.. she gets too close to this upstart, and he seems to be able to sense much.  The Harvest will not lose her to another... Protect her from him boy, or it will be your head.&quot;<br>
<br>
<br>
Daiunus Darkenvalor<br>
Thresher of the Harvest <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub79.ezboard.com/bvhbrell.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=rhysati>Rhysati</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 5<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(1/18/02 5:53:58 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub79.ezboard.com/fvhbrellfrm3.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=195.topic&index=8>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: A spy (I'm sure you've got some) has acquired a letter..</span><hr size=1> Picking her way down the now unfamiliar streets Neriak, Rhysati was headed to the Grange Hall.  Rounding a corner she spied a somewhat familiar face leaving the Hall.  The woman was not hard to miss.  The savage towered over everyone in the street.  &quot;Where have I seen that face before?&quot;...<br>
<br>
&quot;Ahhh, yes, the ceremonies!&quot;  Rhysati shivered at the memory of that night.  Rhys thought to herself &quot;How could I have strayed so far for so long.&quot;<br>
<br>
A young Tier'Dal bursting forth from the Grange at nothing short of a dead sprint roused Rhys from here remembrances, her conflict.  After nearly bowling over a pedestrian, the young lad settled into a casual pace moving up the street.  To most, nothing would have seemed out of the ordinary.  To Rhysati's distrusting eye, something was afoot.  &quot;The Harvest doesn't send Tier'Dal rushing out of the Grange for nothing.&quot;  <br>
<br>
A few moments of observation and Rhys realized the lad was following someone....Who?....The woman, yes...the savage woman.  What was her name?...Payle?...yes.  He's following Payle.   &quot;Hmmm...I think I shall see where this leads...for awhile at least&quot;<br>
<br>
<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#8E236B><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub79.ezboard.com/urohwin.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Rohwin</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 3<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(1/22/02 3:18:06 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub79.ezboard.com/fvhbrellfrm3.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=195.topic&index=9>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: A spy (I'm sure you've got some) has acquired a letter..</span><hr size=1> The Teir'Dal offered as much resistance as expected. A scarce few listened to our words but were quickly overshadowed by General Zirrix. He clearly demonstrated that he remained in control of the woods surrounding Neriak. Teir'Dal would grovel before him and make excuses for their being there, most of which blamed me. As resolved as ever, I continued to preach the benefits of the light, I even recited the thirty rules of courtly love, but few would listen with the general looming over them. I fear that the Teir'Dal are quite determined to remain shrouded in darkness, at least as long as their leaders remain in power. It is a shame, for many that could be saved will certainly fall to the sword. So be it, we did try to save them peaceably in earnest first. We cannot be held responsible if Innoruuk grips them too tight. I keep thinking of that old Human proverb, &quot;Feel no guilt, ye who wields thy blade in the name of Erollisi Marr.&quot; The time for war has not yet come, but I will make sure preparations are underway.<br>
<br>
Even though it seems that the Teir'Dal are to be condemed, I will still try to save the non-Teir'Dal who have fallen under Innoruuk's curse. There is one Barbarian in particular that I will pay attention to. I believe she calls herself Payle. Last time I heard from her she was making explicit threats against me, howsoever, she still listens to what I say. She is defiant for now, but there is hope for her. In time she may yet be saved.<br>
<br>
-excerpt from Rohwin's diary<br>
